President Barack Obama has proclaimed September 2016 as National Alcohol and Drug Addiction Recovery Month in the United States. The proclamation highlights the need for support and treatment for individuals struggling with addiction, and emphasizes the importance of family involvement in the recovery process. It also addresses the misconceptions and stigmas surrounding addiction, and encourages Americans to share their stories and triumphs to inspire others. The proclamation also mentions the steps taken by the Obama administration to combat substance use disorders, such as requiring insurance companies to cover addiction treatment and implementing initiatives to prevent drug use and support recovery. The President urges Congress to fund treatment efforts in order to help more individuals seek help and sustain recovery. The proclamation concludes by calling upon the American people to observe the month with appropriate programs and activities.